where everyone comes out
looking like the Cookie Monster,

44
00:02:48,404 --> 00:02:50,565
whether they want to or not.

45
00:02:50,605 --> 00:02:52,645
And then, suddenly,
it's the weekend,

46
00:02:52,685 --> 00:02:55,285
and from break of day hundreds
of stalls appear out of nowhere,

47
00:02:55,365 --> 00:02:57,925
filling Portobello Road,
right up to Notting Hill Gate.

48
00:02:57,965 --> 00:03:01,405
And wherever you look thousands of
people are buying millions of antiques,

49
00:03:01,485 --> 00:03:06,405
some genuine and some...
not quite so genuine.

50
00:03:06,485 --> 00:03:10,045
And what's great is that lots of friends
have ended up in this part of London.

51
00:03:10,125 --> 00:03:13,485
That's Tony, for example,
architect turned chef,

52
00:03:13,565 --> 00:03:16,845
who recently invested all the money
he ever earned in a new restaurant.

53
00:03:16,925 --> 00:03:19,966
And so, this is where
I spend my days and years...

54
00:03:20,046 --> 00:03:23,726
in this small village in the middle of
the city in a house with a blue door...

55
00:03:23,766 --> 00:03:27,086
that my wife and I bought together
before she left me for a man...

56
00:03:27,166 --> 00:03:29,646
who looked exactly like Harrison Ford.

57
00:03:29,726 --> 00:03:32,566
And where I lead a strange half-life
with a lodger called--

58
00:03:32,646 --> 00:03:34,486
Spike!

59
00:03:38,166 --> 00:03:42,366
You couldn't help me with an incredible
important decision, could you?

60
00:03:42,446 --> 00:03:46,287
Is this important in comparison to,
let's say, whether they should cancel
Third World debt?

61
00:03:46,367 --> 00:03:49,367
That's right. I am at last going out
on a date with the great Janine,

62
00:03:49,447 --> 00:03:51,647
and I just wanna be sure
I've picked the right T-shirt.

63
00:03:51,727 --> 00:03:54,527
- What are the choices?
- Well, wait for it.

64
00:04:01,567 --> 00:04:04,767
First there's this one.
[ Growls ] Cool, huh?

65
00:04:04,927 --> 00:04:09,087
Yeah, it might make it hard
to strike a really romantic note.

66
00:04:09,127 --> 00:04:11,007
Point taken.
Don't despair.

67
00:04:11,047 --> 00:04:14,648
If it's romance we're looking for,
I believe I have just the thing.

68
00:04:18,688 --> 00:04:22,448
Yeah, well, there again, she might not
think you had true love on your mind.

69
00:04:22,528 --> 00:04:25,408
Right.
Just one more.

70
00:04:30,848 --> 00:04:33,208
True love here I come.

71
00:04:38,048 --> 00:04:42,288
Well, yeah. Yeah, that's--
that's, um, perfect.

72
00:04:42,368 --> 00:04:45,209
Great. Thanks.

73
00:04:45,289 --> 00:04:48,449
- Wish me luck.
- Good luck.

74
00:04:53,609 --> 00:04:56,089
[ Narrating ] And so it was
just another hopeless Wednesday,

75
00:04:56,169 --> 00:04:58,809
as I walked the thousand yards
through the market to work,

76
00:04:58,889 --> 00:05:03,249
never suspecting that this was the day
that was gonna change my life forever.

77
00:05:03,329 --> 00:05:06,649
This is work, by the way,
my little travel bookshop,

78
00:05:07,689 --> 00:05:10,649
- Morning, Martin.
- Morning, Monsignor.

79
00:05:10,689 --> 00:05:13,610
which, um, well, sells travel books,

80
00:05:13,690 --> 00:05:16,930
and to be frank with you,
doesn't always sell many of those.

81
00:05:20,450 --> 00:05:23,850
Classic.
Profit from major sales push,

82
00:05:23,930 --> 00:05:26,890
minus 347 pounds.

83
00:05:28,410 --> 00:05:31,890
Shall l, uh,
go and get you a cappuccino?

84
00:05:31,970 --> 00:05:34,810
- You know, ease the pain a bit.
- Yeah, yeah.

85
00:05:34,890 --> 00:05:37,850
Better make it a half.
All I can afford.

86
00:05:37,930 --> 00:05:42,571
Get your logic.
Demi-cappu coming right up.

87
00:05:42,651 --> 00:05:44,971
[ Doorbell Dings ]

88
00:06:05,771 --> 00:06:08,091
Um, can I help you at all?

89
00:06:09,412 --> 00:06:12,572
No, thanks.
I'll just... look around.

90
00:06:13,612 --> 00:06:16,332
Fine.

91
00:06:21,572 --> 00:06:24,652
Uh, that book's really not great.

92
00:06:24,732 --> 00:06:28,572
Just in case, you know, browsing turned
to buying. You'd be wasting your money.

93
00:06:28,652 --> 00:06:31,052
But if it's Turkey
you're interested in,

94
00:06:31,132 --> 00:06:34,012
um, this one, on the other hand,
is very good.

95
00:06:34,092 --> 00:06:38,173
Um, I think the man who wrote it has
actually been to Turkey, which helps.

96
00:06:38,213 --> 00:06:41,973
Um, there's also
a very amusing incident with a kebab,

97
00:06:42,053 --> 00:06:44,693
um, which is one
of many amusing incidents.

98
00:06:44,773 --> 00:06:46,653
Thanks.
I'll think about it.

99
00:06:46,693 --> 00:06:49,133
Or, in the bigger hardback variety,
there's--

100
00:06:49,213 --> 00:06:53,093
I'm sorry.
Can you just give me a second?

101
00:06:56,133 --> 00:06:58,253
Excuse me.

102
00:06:58,333 --> 00:07:00,253
- Yes?
- Bad news.

103
00:07:00,333 --> 00:07:01,733
What?

104
00:07:01,773 --> 00:07:05,213
We've got a security camera
in this bit of the shop.

105
00:07:05,293 --> 00:07:06,494
So?

106
00:07:06,574 --> 00:07:09,214
So I saw you put that book
down your trousers.

107
00:07:10,534 --> 00:07:14,574
- What book?
- The one down your trousers.

108
00:07:14,654 --> 00:07:17,134
I don't have a book
down my trousers.

109
00:07:17,214 --> 00:07:19,094
Right.

110
00:07:19,174 --> 00:07:21,374
I tell you what.
Um, I'll call the police, and, um,

111
00:07:21,414 --> 00:07:25,094
if I'm wrong about the whole
"book down the trousers" scenario,

112
00:07:25,174 --> 00:07:26,534
I really apologize.

113
00:07:26,614 --> 00:07:31,774
Okay. What if... I did
have a book down my trousers?

114
00:07:31,814 --> 00:07:34,575
Well, ideally,
when I went back to the desk,

115
00:07:34,655 --> 00:07:39,535
you'd remove the Cadogan Guide
to Bali from your trousers...

116
00:07:39,615 --> 00:07:42,655
and either wipe it
and put it back or buy it.

117
00:07:42,735 --> 00:07:45,055
I'll see you in a sec.

118
00:07:45,095 --> 00:07:47,495
I'm sorry about that.

119
00:07:47,535 --> 00:07:49,975
No, it's fine.

120
00:07:50,055 --> 00:07:53,775
I was gonna steal one,
but now I've changed my mind.

121
00:07:53,855 --> 00:07:56,655
Oh, signed by the author,
I see.

122
00:07:56,735 --> 00:07:58,975
Um, yeah, couldn't stop him.

123
00:07:59,015 --> 00:08:01,815
If you can find an unsigned one,
it's worth an absolute fortune.

124
00:08:01,895 --> 00:08:04,736
- [ Chuckles ]
- Excuse me.

125
00:08:04,816 --> 00:08:06,776
- Yes?
- Can I have your autograph?

126
00:08:06,856 --> 00:08:09,216
Uh, sure.

127
00:08:09,256 --> 00:08:11,296
- Uh--
- Here.

128
00:08:11,376 --> 00:08:14,736
- What's your name?
- Rufus.

129
00:08:19,296 --> 00:08:21,216
What does it say?

130
00:08:21,256 --> 00:08:26,136
That's my signature. And above it, it
says, "Dear Rufus, you belong in jail."

131
00:08:26,216 --> 00:08:28,216
Good one.

132
00:08:29,896 --> 00:08:33,297
- Do you want my phone number?
- Tempting.

133
00:08:33,377 --> 00:08:36,097
But... no.
Thank you.

134
00:08:39,817 --> 00:08:42,577
I will take this one.

135
00:08:42,657 --> 00:08:45,017
Oh, right, right.
So, uh--

136
00:08:45,097 --> 00:08:48,977
Well, on second thoughts,
um, maybe it's not that bad after all.

137
00:08:49,057 --> 00:08:51,817
Actually, it's a sort
of a classic, really.

138
00:08:51,897 --> 00:08:55,297
None of those childish kebab stories
you find in so many books these days.

139
00:08:55,377 --> 00:08:57,257
And, um, I tell you what.

140
00:08:57,297 --> 00:08:59,217
I'll throw in
one of those for free.

141
00:08:59,297 --> 00:09:01,698
Useful for, uh, lighting fires,

142
00:09:01,778 --> 00:09:04,618
wrapping fish,
that sort of thing.

143
00:09:07,378 --> 00:09:09,778
- Thanks.
- Pleasure.

144
00:09:19,858 --> 00:09:22,178
[ Door Closes ]

145
00:09:39,659 --> 00:09:43,859
Cappuccino, as ordered.

146
00:09:43,939 --> 00:09:45,859
Thanks.

147
00:09:45,939 --> 00:09:48,899
I don't think you'll believe
who was just in here.

148
00:09:48,979 --> 00:09:51,739
Who?
Was it someone famous?

149
00:09:53,099 --> 00:09:55,099
- No, no, no.
- No?

150
00:09:55,179 --> 00:09:59,500
Would be exciting, though,
wouldn't it, if someone famous
came into the shop? Hmm?

151
00:09:59,580 --> 00:10:03,380
Do you know--
and this is pretty amazing, actually--

152
00:10:03,460 --> 00:10:05,620
but I once saw Ringo Starr.

153
00:10:05,700 --> 00:10:07,900
- Where was that?
- Kensington High Street.

154
00:10:07,980 --> 00:10:09,820
At least I think it was Ringo.

155
00:10:09,900 --> 00:10:12,500
It might have been that man
from Fiddler on the Roof.

156
00:10:12,580 --> 00:10:15,140
- You know, Toppy.
- Topol.

157
00:10:15,180 --> 00:10:17,780
Yes, that's right.
Topol.

158
00:10:17,860 --> 00:10:19,700
Mm-hmm.

159
00:10:19,780 --> 00:10:23,500
Actually, Ringo Starr doesn't--
doesn't look at all like, uh, Topol.

160
00:10:23,540 --> 00:10:26,501
Yeah, but he was--
he was quite a long way away from me.

161
00:10:26,581 --> 00:10:29,541
So actually it could've
been neither of them.

162
00:10:29,621 --> 00:10:32,381
Yes, I suppose so, yes.

163
00:10:32,461 --> 00:10:36,661
- It's not a classic anecdote, is it?
- Not a classic, no. No.

164
00:10:40,301 --> 00:10:44,581
- Another one?
- [ Sighs ] Yes. No.

165
00:10:44,621 --> 00:10:47,941
Let's go crazy.
I'll have an orange juice.

166
00:10:48,021 --> 00:10:50,861
[ People Chattering ]

167
00:10:53,261 --> 00:10:55,942
- Okay, thanks. Bye-bye.
- See you later.

168
00:11:02,582 --> 00:11:04,542
- Oh!
- Oh! Shit!

169
00:11:04,622 --> 00:11:07,462
- Oh, my God!
- Bugger! I'm so sorry. I'm so sorry.

170
00:11:07,542 --> 00:11:10,302
- Here. Let me--
- Get your hands off!

171
00:11:10,382 --> 00:11:13,062
I'm really sorry.
I- I live just over the street.

172
00:11:13,102 --> 00:11:16,222
I have, um, water and soap.
You can get cleaned up.

173
00:11:16,302 --> 00:11:18,422
No, thank you.
I just need to get my car back.

174
00:11:18,502 --> 00:11:21,702
I also have a phone.
I'm confident that in five minutes...

175
00:11:21,742 --> 00:11:24,623
we could have you spick-and-span
and back on the street again.

176
00:11:24,663 --> 00:11:27,303
In the non-prostitute sense,
obviously.

177
00:11:30,263 --> 00:11:33,343
All right. Well-- What do you mean,
"just over the street"?

178
00:11:33,423 --> 00:11:36,983
- Give it to me in yards.
- Uh, 18 yards.

179
00:11:37,063 --> 00:11:40,143
That's my house there
with the blue front door.

180
00:11:42,983 --> 00:11:46,063
Come on in.
I'll just-- I'll just--

181
00:11:49,063 --> 00:11:53,944
Um, right. Right.
Come in.

182
00:11:54,024 --> 00:11:57,264
It's, um, not quite as tidy
as it normally is, I fear.

183
00:11:57,344 --> 00:12:00,384
But, um--
The bathroom's on the top floor.

184
00:12:00,424 --> 00:12:04,144
And the telephone's just--
just up here.

185
00:12:05,664 --> 00:12:07,904
Here.
Let-- Let me, um--

186
00:12:13,464 --> 00:12:16,744
Um, round the corner.
Straight on-- straight on up.

187
00:12:20,425 --> 00:12:22,265
Bugger.

188
00:12:23,465 --> 00:12:25,345
[ Groans ]

189
00:12:26,985 --> 00:12:28,785
Uh-oh.

190
00:12:41,105 --> 00:12:42,945
Uh,

191
00:12:42,985 --> 00:12:46,065
would you like a cup of tea
before you go?

192
00:12:46,145 --> 00:12:48,385
- No.
- Coffee?

193
00:12:48,466 --> 00:12:51,106
- No.
- Orange juice?

194
00:12:52,226 --> 00:12:56,506
Probably not.
Um, something else cold.

195
00:12:56,586 --> 00:12:58,426
Uh--

196
00:12:58,506 --> 00:13:02,466
- [ Bottles Rattling ]
- Coke? Water?

197
00:13:02,506 --> 00:13:04,386
Some disgusting sugary drink...

198
00:13:04,426 --> 00:13:06,466
pretending to have something to do
with fruits of the forest?

199
00:13:06,506 --> 00:13:09,466
- No.
- Would you like something to eat?

200
00:13:09,546 --> 00:13:11,706
Uh, something to nibble?

201
00:13:11,786 --> 00:13:15,466
Um, apricots soaked in honey?

202
00:13:15,546 --> 00:13:18,827
Quite why, no one knows, because
it stops them tasting of apricots...

203
00:13:18,907 --> 00:13:21,147
and makes them taste like honey,

204
00:13:21,227 --> 00:13:25,947
and if you wanted honey, you'd just
buy honey instead of... apricots.

205
00:13:26,027 --> 00:13:28,427
Um, but nevertheless,
there we go there.

206
00:13:28,467 --> 00:13:30,547
They're yours if you want them.

207
00:13:30,627 --> 00:13:32,387
No.

208
00:13:34,827 --> 00:13:37,147
Do you always say "no"
to everything?

209
00:13:38,987 --> 00:13:40,867
No.

210
00:13:42,347 --> 00:13:44,867
I'd better be going.

211
00:13:44,907 --> 00:13:48,068
Thanks for your, uh, help.

212
00:13:48,108 --> 00:13:49,988
You're welcome.

213
00:13:50,028 --> 00:13:55,188
And, uh, may I also say,
um, heavenly.

214
00:13:55,268 --> 00:13:58,068
I'll just take
my one chance to say it.

215
00:13:58,148 --> 00:14:00,308
After you've read
that terrible book,

216
00:14:00,388 --> 00:14:02,628
you're certainly not going
to be coming back to the shop.

217
00:14:02,668 --> 00:14:05,188
Thank you.

218
00:14:05,268 --> 00:14:09,068
Yeah.
Well, my pleasure.

219
00:14:19,189 --> 00:14:21,829
So...

220
00:14:21,909 --> 00:14:23,909
it was nice to meet you.

221
00:14:23,949 --> 00:14:28,069
Surreal but, um-- but nice.

222
00:14:30,029 --> 00:14:31,909
Sorry.

223
00:14:31,949 --> 00:14:34,789
[ People Chattering Outside ]

224
00:14:39,109 --> 00:14:42,429
"Surreal but nice"?
What was I thinking?

225
00:14:47,950 --> 00:14:50,790
[ Doorbell Rings ]

226
00:14:53,630 --> 00:14:56,030
- Hi.
- Hi.

227
00:14:56,110 --> 00:15:00,030
- I forgot my other bag.
- Oh, right. Right.

228
00:15:08,470 --> 00:15:10,350
Thanks.

229
00:15:39,631 --> 00:15:44,232
I'm very sorry about
the "surreal but nice" comment.

230
00:15:44,272 --> 00:15:46,672
- Disaster.
- That's okay.

231
00:15:46,712 --> 00:15:51,272
I thought the apricot and honey thing
was the real low point.

232
00:15:51,352 --> 00:15:53,312
- [ Chuckles ]
- [ Doorknob Rattling ]

233
00:15:53,392 --> 00:15:55,992
Oh, my God.
My flatmate.

234
00:15:56,072 --> 00:15:58,632
I'm sorry.
There's no excuse for him.

235
00:15:58,672 --> 00:16:01,032
[ Clears Throat ]

236
00:16:01,072 --> 00:16:02,952
- Hey.
- Hi.

237
00:16:02,992 --> 00:16:05,272
I'm just going into the kitchen
to get some food.

238
00:16:05,352 --> 00:16:09,513
Then I'm gonna tell you a story
that will make your balls shrink
to the size of raisins.

239
00:16:14,233 --> 00:16:17,673
Probably best
not to tell anyone about this.

240
00:16:17,753 --> 00:16:20,633
Right. Right.
No one.

